  "text": "The etcd client-side retry and timeout policy is implemented across several key components in the GitHub repository github.com/etcd-io/etcd:\n\n## Retry Interceptor Implementation\n\nThe core retry logic is implemented in `client/v3/retry_interceptor.go`. This file contains two main interceptors:\n\n1. **unaryClientInterceptor** (line 41): Handles retry for unary gRPC calls. It implements a loop-based retry mechanism with configurable maximum retries, backoff strategies, and context deadline handling. For each failed attempt, it checks if the error is safe to retry using `isSafeRetry()`, manages token refresh for authentication failures, and respects context cancellations.\n\n2. **streamClientInterceptor** (line 112): Handles retry for server-side streaming calls. It wraps the stream in a `serverStreamingRetryingStream` (line 188) that buffers sent messages and implements `RecvMsg()` retry logic. This is critical for Watch operations which use bidirectional streaming.\n\nKey retry support functions include:\n- **waitRetryBackoff** (line 312): Implements backoff delay between retries using `backoffLinearWithJitter` with a default 50ms jitter\n- **isSafeRetry** (line 330 in retry_interceptor.go): Determines if an error is retryable based on error type and retry policy\n\n## Retry Policy and Safety Checks\n\nThe `client/v3/retry.go` file implements detailed retry safety logic:\n\n1. **isSafeRetryImmutableRPC** (line 54): Immutable requests (Get) can be safely retried on any transient error except server-specific errors like ErrCompacted. Only retries on `codes.Unavailable`.\n\n2. **isSafeRetryMutableRPC** (line 85): Mutable requests (Put, Delete, Txn) can only be retried when there's no connection available (`codes.Unavailable` with specific error descriptions). This enforces write-at-most-once semantics.\n\n3. **RetryKVClient** (line 101): Wraps the KV client to apply retry policies. Range operations use `withRepeatablePolicy()` for retries, while Put/Delete/Txn operations follow the default non-repeatable policy.\n\n4. **RetryLeaseClient** (line 132): Similar wrapper for Lease operations, marking read operations as repeatable.\n\n## Endpoint Balancer and Resolver\n\nThe `client/v3/internal/resolver/resolver.go` file implements:\n\n1. **EtcdManualResolver** (line 31): A gRPC resolver that maintains the list of available endpoints and updates the load balancer. It uses `round_robin` load balancing policy (line 44) and supports dynamic endpoint updates via `SetEndpoints()`.\n\n2. **updateState** (line 62): Converts endpoint strings to gRPC resolver endpoints with proper address and server name interpretation for TLS validation.\n\nThe resolver is integrated into the client dial process through `dialWithBalancer()` in client.go (line 310-322), which uses the resolver to provide endpoints to the gRPC connection.\n\n## Timeout and KeepAlive Configuration\n\nThe `client/v3/config.go` file defines critical timeout parameters:\n\n1. **DialTimeout** (line 36-37): Timeout for establishing initial connection, used in `dialSetupOpts()` with `context.WithTimeout()`\n\n2. **DialKeepAliveTime** (line 39-41): Time interval between client-to-server keepalive pings\n\n3. **DialKeepAliveTimeout** (line 43-45): Timeout waiting for keepalive response before closing connection\n\n4. **PermitWithoutStream** (line 64): Allows keepalive pings even without active RPCs\n\nThese are applied in `client/v3/client.go` at line 227-237 in the `dialSetupOpts()` function using `keepalive.ClientParameters`.\n\n## Connection Health Check\n\nThe `waitForConnection()` function (line 344 in client.go) performs a gRPC health check before accepting the connection:\n- Uses `healthpb.NewHealthClient().Check()` with `grpc.WaitForReady(true)`\n- Tolerates `Unimplemented` (server without health endpoint) and `FailedPrecondition` (leader not yet applied config)\n- Implements timeout using `withMax(0)` to disable retry on health check failures\n\n## KV Operations\n\